message.content:
**Analysis of Target Image**

The target shows _two separate little builds_:  
1) **“House” on the left**  
   • **Bottom Layer** – A yellow rectangular beam bridging between two blue cubes.  
   • **Middle “Wall”** – Two red cubes stacked vertically on top of the yellow beam.  
   • **Green Band** – A single green rectangular block laid horizontally atop the red cubes.  
   • **Roof** – Two orange wedge‐shaped pieces meeting at the apex.  

   Counting each cube/beam/wedge as a separate piece, the house uses 8 blocks total.  
   If you count strictly by horizontal “layers,” there are effectively 5 layers (blue + yellow on the bottom, then two red‐cube layers, then a green layer, then the orange roof layer).  

2) **“Arch” on the right**  
   • **Bottom Green Block** – One green rectangular block laid flat.  
   • **Yellow Pillars** – Two tall yellow blocks standing vertically (left and right sides).  
   • **Top Green Block** – Another green rectangular block laid flat on top of the pillars.  
   • **Center Wedge** – A single orange wedge block standing inside the arch.  

   This arch uses 5 blocks total over three main layers (green base; the two yellow pillars in the middle layer plus the wedge between them; and the green top block).  

Altogether, there are 13 blocks across both sub‐assemblies.

---

**Blocks Chosen From the Dictionary**

Below is the exact mapping from the Dictionary (second image) to each piece in the final build. (Note that some entries are reused multiple times.)

• **Blue Cubes (House bottom)**:  
  – Use block index 1 (blue cube) for the left and right footings.  

• **Red Cubes (House wall)**:  
  – Use block index 2 (red cube) twice (stacked) for the center wall.  

• **Yellow Horizontal Beam (House)**:  
  – Use block index 7 (yellow rectangular prism, oriented lengthwise) as the bridging piece along the bottom.  

• **Green Horizontal Block (House)**:  
  – Use block index 5 (green block oriented flat) for the band just under the roof.  

• **Orange Roof Wedges (House)**:  
  – Use block index 13 for the left roof slope.  
  – Use block index 16 for the right roof slope.  

• **Green Blocks (Arch bottom & top)**:  
  – Use block index 5 again (three total times in this build) for both the bottom and top of the arch.  

• **Tall Yellow Pillars (Arch sides)**:  
  – Use block index 9 for the left pillar.  
  – Use block index 10 for the right pillar (same shape, different “no‐rotation” orientation).  

• **Orange Wedge (Arch center)**:  
  – Use block index 14 for the wedge that sits in the middle of the arch.  

---

**Assembly Order**

A suitable step‐by‐step sequence (placing the House first, then the Arch) is:

{
  Step1: Move block with index 1   // House: blue cube (bottom left)  
  Step2: Move block with index 1   // House: blue cube (bottom right)  
  Step3: Move block with index 7   // House: yellow horizontal beam  
  Step4: Move block with index 2   // House: first red cube  
  Step5: Move block with index 2   // House: second red cube (stack on the first)  
  Step6: Move block with index 5   // House: green flat block  
  Step7: Move block with index 13  // House: left orange roof wedge  
  Step8: Move block with index 16  // House: right orange roof wedge  

  Step9:  Move block with index 5  // Arch: green base  
  Step10: Move block with index 9  // Arch: left tall yellow pillar  
  Step11: Move block with index 10 // Arch: right tall yellow pillar  
  Step12: Move block with index 5  // Arch: green top block  
  Step13: Move block with index 14 // Arch: orange wedge inside the arch  
}

Following these steps with the exact dictionary indices (and without rotating any pieces) reproduces the target structures as shown.
